&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br>
<big>24.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Prepositions with the
dative
case</big><br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The preposition most commonly used with the dative
case is &#1087;&#1072;.&nbsp; There are many different meanings of &#1087;&#1072; + dative, but
a few examples are given below.&nbsp; For these usages, the preposition
&#1087;&#1072; only takes the dative when the indirect object is singular.&nbsp; If
the object is plural, it must take the prepositional case.<br>
<br>
<table style="width: 500px; text-align: left;" border="0"
 cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">&#1071; &#1076;&#1072;&#1118; &#1076;&#1079;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1077;</span>&#1094;&#1103;&#1084; &#1087;&#1072; <span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1103;</span>&#1073;&#1083;&#1099;&#1082;&#1091;.<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-style: italic;">I
gave the children one apple apiece.</span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">&#1055;&#1072;&#1083;&#1103;&#1118;&#1085;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1110;</span>&#1095;&#1099; &#1110;&#1076;&#1079;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1077;</span> &#1087;&#1072; &#1089;&#1083;&#1103;&#1076;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1072;</span>&#1093; &#1079;&#1074;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1077;</span>&#1088;&#1072;.<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-style: italic;">The
hunter went along the animal's tracks.</span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">&#1057;&#1087;&#1072;&#1073;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1086;</span>&#1088;&#1085;&#1110;&#1094;&#1090;&#1074;&#1099; &#1087;&#1072; &#1092;&#1091;&#1090;&#1073;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1086;</span>&#1083;&#1091;.<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-style: italic;">Soccer
competition.</span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">&#1053;&#1077; &#1087;&#1088;&#1099;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1077;</span>&#1093;&#1072;&#1118; &#1087;&#1072; &#1093;&#1074;&#1072;&#1088;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1086;</span>&#1073;&#1077;.<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-style: italic;">He
did not come because he was sick.</span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">&#1058;&#1072;&#1074;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1072;</span>&#1088;&#1099;&#1096; &#1087;&#1072; &#1091;&#1085;&#1110;&#1074;&#1077;&#1088;&#1089;&#1110;&#1090;<span
 style="text-decoration: underline;">&#1101;</span>&#1090;&#1091;.<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-style: italic;">A
friend from college.</span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<br>
&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The preposition &#1082; is also used with the dative
case.&nbsp; This preposition is not as common in Belarusian as it is in
Russian.&nbsp; Often, the preposition &#1076;&#1072; is used in Belarusian in
situations where Russian uses &#1082;.<br>
<br>
